as.leap

Class LCObject

  • java.lang.Object
    • as.leap.LCObject
  • Direct Known Subclasses:
    LCInstallation, LCRole

    public class LCObject
extends java.lang.Object
    The LCObject is a local representation of data that can be saved and retrieved from the LC cloud.

      • setObjectId

        public void setObjectId(java.lang.String objectId)
        Setter for the object id. In general you do not need to use this. However, in some cases this can be convenient. For example, if you are serializing a LCObject yourself and wish to recreate it, you can use this to recreate the LCObject exactly.
        Parameters:
        objectId - the objectId

      • getObjectId

        public java.lang.String getObjectId()
        Accessor to the object id. An object id is assigned as soon as an object is saved to the server. The combination of a className and an objectId uniquely identifies an object in your application.
        Returns:
        the objectId

      • getCreatedAt

        public java.util.Date getCreatedAt()
        This reports time as the server sees it, so that if you create a LCObject, then wait a while, and then call save(), the creation time will be the time of the first save() call rather than the time the object was created locally.
        Returns:
        The first time this object was saved on the server.

      • getUpdatedAt

        public java.util.Date getUpdatedAt()
        This reports time as the server sees it, so that if you make changes to a LCObject, then wait a while, and then call save(), the updated time will be the time of the save() call rather than the time the object was changed locally.
        Returns:
        The last time this object was updated on the server.

      • removeAll

        public void removeAll(java.lang.String key,
                      java.util.Collection<?> values)
        Atomically removes all instances of the objects contained in a Collection from the array associated with a given key. To maintain consistency with the Java Collection API, there is no method removing all instances of a single object. Instead, you can call LCObject.removeAll(key, Arrays.asList(value)).
        Parameters:
        key - The key.
        values - The objects to remove.

      • createWithoutData

        public static <T extends LCObject> T createWithoutData(java.lang.String className,
                                                       java.lang.String objectId)
        Creates a reference to an existing LCObject for use in creating associations between LCObjects. Calling LCObject.isDataAvailable() on this object will return false until LCDataManage.fetchInBackground() has been called. No network request will be made.
        Parameters:
        className - the class name
        objectId - the objectId
        Returns:
        a LCObject

      • createWithoutData

        public static <T extends LCObject> T createWithoutData(java.lang.Class<T> subClass,
                                                       java.lang.String objectId)
        Creates a reference to an existing LCObject for use in creating associations between LCObjects. Calling LCObject.isDataAvailable() on this object will return false until LCObject.fetchIfNeeded() or LCObject.refresh() has been called. No network request will be made.
        Parameters:
        subClass - The LCObject subclass to create.
        objectId - The object id for the referenced object.
        Returns:
        A LCObject without data.
